        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <date>5<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. Feb<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>. 1876.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Darwin</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I wrote to you this morning when the teapot was a proposal merely. It has now come, and any thing more exquisite than it and its appurtenances I have never seen.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Louisa<ref target="#foot.f2"/> was with me when it arrived and she could not find words to express her sense of your kindness. “What shall we say to him” I asked. “How shall we thank him?” “Say” said she simply “that the gift is worthy of the giver. Nothing higher can be said regarding it”.</p>
<p>Yours to the last | John Tyndall</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD had probably sent a tea set, rather than simply a teapot, from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_7530.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Boone Thomas</ref> &amp; Co. (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10379.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to John Tyndall, 4 February 1876</ref> and n. 2).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Louisa Charlotte Hamilton, Tyndall’s fiancée.</note>
        </div>        
            
